Rupert Thomas Webb (11 July 1922 – 27 August 2018) was an English cricketer who played first-class cricket for Sussex from 1948 to 1960. He was born in Harrow, Middlesex.
Webb was Sussex's regular wicketkeeper between 1950 and 1958. In all, he played in 255 first-class matches for the county, plus one for the Marylebone Cricket Club in 1959 when he was no longer playing regularly for Sussex.

He made 25 further first-class appearances for the county, the last of which came against Essex in the 1958 County Championship.  In his 26 first-class matches for Sussex, he scored a total of 150 runs at an average of 6.00, with a high score of 34.  Behind the stumps he took 28 catches and made 2 stumpings.  Mantell found his opportunities limited, and when the regular Sussex wicketkeeper Rupert Webb announced he would retire from full-time cricket at the end of the 1958 season, Sussex encouraged Jim Parks, a far better batsman than Mantell, to take up wicketkeeping; that led Mantell to leave the county at the end of the 1958 season.
